{"type":"message","id":"cf2e0738","parentId":"924ab31c","timestamp":"2026-04-13T11:00:44.625Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Hmm, I see that `killall -c chrome` didn't actually kill the chrome processes in the vibesurf-1 container. The processes are still running. That's because those chrome processes are running inside the vibesurf-1 container, and the container's processes are not visible/killable from the host via regular `killall`. \n\nThe chrome processes I see are all from PID 1522858 onwards which is the vibesurf container's chrome. They're still running because they were in a different PID namespace.\n\nActually wait, looking more carefully - the `killall -c chrome` returned \"done\" with exit code 0 but there are still 21 chrome processes. \n\nSo the issue is that `killall` running on the host can only signal processes in the host's PID namespace, but those chrome processes belong to the container's namespace. I need to either kill them from inside the container using `docker exec`, or find another way to target processes that are isolated within the containerized environment."},{"type":"text","text":"`killall` 没起作用——那些 chrome 跑在容器 `vibesurf-1` 的命名空间里，宿主机上的 kill 触及不到它们。需要从容器内部杀。\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_xpo71tb1jqjv_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker exec vibesurf-1 killall chrome 2>&1; echo \"exit: $?\""}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776078033003,"responseId":"062bffd1a8ff1ca8949d7bd54604de73"}}
